Obviously it's better if we can find ways of reducing that margin of error - without introducing new vulnerabilities (like hacking).
The smaller the election (or key subdivision of an election, as in Florida 2000), the more material any given voting fraud or error becomes.
It became material because the margin of victory came down to a few hundred votes in a single decisive state - a very unusual situation.
No one wants to admit it, but there's an unavoidable margin of error in all elections, due to error. In 2000, that margin became material.
A related question is whether voting fraud and/or mistakes systematically favors one side or the other, or if it's just white noise.
